content.text: Currently I’m working on a gallery in Pulp called 'The D.B. Keplar Art Gallery'. The project started out while I was experimenting with art ideas inside the Pulp editor. Most of the time when I begin working on a project I have a more clearly defined central idea or story I want to tell. In this case I originally felt like making an exploreable space that is largely undefined and more abstract in its storytelling. I invited a focus on experimentation, free association and atmosphere. When I started to work with Pulp I soon realized how it would be an ideal environment for this approach.
Most of the game is made directly in Pulp, but there are a few rooms that I drew in Aseprite and imported as tiles into pulp.

content.text: Three doors connecting different parts of the gallery.

It’s hard to describe exactly what this ‘game’ is because of its rather abstract nature. One of the greater challenges in working on this project is trying to offer enough of a relatable game experience while also portraying an abstract art gallery that grows organically from the art pieces but doesn’t push fixed interpretations on the players/visitors. To say that this game tells a deeper story or has a single clear message would perhaps be a bit of a stretch, yet there are thematic patterns and ideas that do reflect on certain artistic, emotional and social topics.
